description:
Lowest elevation plant I found on Spray Park trail. There is one a few meters lower reported but it is probably the same cluster as this once, since the uncertainty overlaps and it maps in woods, which probably is not right.

This species probably grows in lower (but still nearly subalpine) meadows. This was in the first significant meadow on this trail.

There is one report on iNat along Mowich Lake side meadow, with high uncertainty but text description suggesting that it is indeed next to the lake but I couldn't find the plant.

Whole plant view for records. This species is extremely abundant locally (e.g. https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/234979471) so I hope pulling up a plant is not a big deal. I had no convenient tool and the root did not come up, but Burke Herbarium says that it has a "thickened taproot".

This plant includes a reduced leaf from a flower stem, which is not very common. This is about the maximum length for the floral stem.
This globally rare endemic is abundant in some places. All of the yellow flowers in photo 1.
When in flower, it is easier to get a sense of how abundant this is in some areas (first and last photos). Flowers passed in warmer areas, but still mostly in flower in upper Spray Park.
As at Grand Park, abundant in much of Spray Park. Still in flower in cooler spots, this was the most mature fruit at this time, lagging Grand Park by about a week or two.
Unusual plant with purple leaves, perhaps just early fall color.
Common in parts of Grand Park, often the most common plant, approaching a ground cover. Foliage 1-2 inches tall and fruits 6-9 inches tall. Occasionally slight taller foliage.
